xf86-video-crime - Xorg driver for the SGI O2 CRIME rendering engine
====================================================================

An Xorg driver for the CRIME rendering engine found in SGI O2
workstations, based on the NetBSD xsrc driver by Michael Lorenz,
repackaged with modern autotools and ported to the current
xorg-server API.

All rendering goes through the CRIME engine: the visible framebuffer
is tiled and not usefully CPU addressable, so the driver keeps a
malloc'ed shadow for fb fallbacks and transfers pixels with the XAA
ImageWrite/ReadPixmap hooks.  An X server with XAA support is
therefore required.

Backends
--------

* NetBSD/OpenBSD (wscons): the classic behaviour - the wsdisplay
  device (default /dev/ttyE0) provides mode switching, colormap,
  blanking and the hardware cursor, and the engine is mapped through
  the wsdisplay mmap interface.

* Linux (gbefb): the framebuffer console device (default /dev/fb0,
  driver "SGI GBE") provides the display information, colormap and
  blanking; the CRIME engine at physical 0x15000000 and the GBE
  display backend at 0x16000000 are mapped through /dev/mem.  The
  32x32 GBE hardware cursor is programmed directly through the
  CRMFB cursor registers.

  Unlike NetBSD, where the crmfb kernel driver sets up the CRIME
  rendering engine at attach time, the Linux gbefb driver only knows
  about the GBE scanout.  The X driver therefore takes over the
  hardware itself at ScreenInit:

  - it carves a tile-aligned framebuffer (visible screen plus
    offscreen pixmap space), a 128kB DMA staging buffer and a GBE
    tile pointer table out of the physically contiguous gbefb video
    memory (fix.smem_start/smem_len),
  - programs the rendering engine's TLB A and first linear TLB with
    that layout (without this, any access to the engine apertures
    raises a hardware bus error - "Bus error at address 0x0"),
  - and switches the GBE scanout from gbefb's linear one-tile-wide
    trick to the native tiled layout the engine renders into.  The
    previous state is restored on VT switch and server exit so fbcon
    keeps working.

  Requirements: a 32bpp mode (the driver switches the fbdev to
  32bpp itself, or boot with video=gbefb:depth:32) and enough gbefb
  memory for the tiled screen: e.g. 1280x1024 needs 8 rows of 10
  tiles (5MB) plus 192kB - boot with gbefb mem=8M or more.  Any
  extra gbefb memory (up to 16 tile rows) becomes offscreen pixmap
  cache.

  Video modes: the mode gbefb is programmed to at server start is
  auto-detected from /dev/fb0, always part of the mode pool, and is
  the startup mode.  The rest of the pool is built with the standard
  Xorg validation: the Monitor section's modelines and the built-in
  default modes, limited by the monitor's HorizSync/VertRefresh
  ranges and Option "MaxClock" from xorg.conf (conservative defaults
  apply when none are given), and by what gbefb itself accepts - it
  computes its dot clock PLL from the modeline, so arbitrary
  modelines up to 2048x2048, non-interlaced, work.  Modes switch at
  runtime via Ctrl+Alt+Keypad-Plus/Minus, the XFree86-VidMode
  extension or RandR; each switch reprograms the GBE timings through
  FBIOPUT_VSCREENINFO and re-takes the scanout.  The tiled
  framebuffer is laid out for the largest (virtual) size; smaller
  modes scan out its top-left corner (no viewport panning).

The device can be overridden with Option "device" in the Device
section, or the XDEVICE environment variable.

Building
--------

  ./autogen.sh --prefix=/usr
  make
  make install
